vely their own priorities through their translations, verse and letters. By reconstructing the sisters’ networks, it demonstrates how they worked alongside – and sometimes against – family members over matters of politics and religion, empowered by their exceptional education. Providing new perspectives on these key issues, it will be essential reading for early modern historians and literary scholars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aUpper class womenxEducationxHistoryx16th centuryxEngland. 0aUpper class womenxEducationzEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aUpper class womenxSocial conditionsx16th centuryxEngland. 0aUpper class womenzEnglandxSocial conditionsy16th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aCooke sisters' classical learning.  aCooke sisters' education.  aCooke sisters' reading.  aElizabethan diplomacy.  aElizabethan politics.  aTudor political culture.  afemale counsel.  afemale humanists.  ahumanist education.  alearned women.  amid-sixteenth-century England.  apolitical activities.  areligion.  asixteenth-century women.  astereotype.1 aAllen, Gemma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611195140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526111951423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526111951/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles